188e249ce5"><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'>A few =
weeks ago I sold a product I had created and run with my =
cofounder.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p =
style=3D'mso-margin-top-alt:7.5pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:15.0pt;m=
argin-left:0cm;color:#111!important;line-height:1.6!important;letter-spac=
ing:-0.007em!important'><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'>We had =
been working on it since 2016 and it was profitable (making thousands a =
month and costing less than a thousand a year in expenses). Over the =
years, we had amassed over a thousand customers.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p =
style=3D'mso-margin-top-alt:7.5pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:15.0pt;m=
argin-left:0cm;color:#111!important;line-height:1.6!important;letter-spac=
ing:-0.007em!important'><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'>But when =
the right buyer came along, who offered the right price, we decided to =
sell it. How come?&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p><p =
style=3D'mso-margin-top-alt:7.5pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:15.0pt;m=
argin-left:0cm;color:#111!important;line-height:1.6!important;letter-spac=
ing:-0.007em!important'><em><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'>(This is =
obviously my own point of view, since I don't want to speak for my =
cofounder.)</span></em><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'><o:p></o:p>=
</span></p><p =
style=3D'mso-margin-top-alt:7.5pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:15.0pt;m=
argin-left:0cm;color:#111!important;line-height:1.6!important;letter-spac=
ing:-0.007em!important'><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'>The main =
reason I wanted to sell is that there's a huge difference between being =
a starter and being an operator. A starter has the vision to create a =
product or business from nothing, and build it out. The skillset here is =
mostly creativity, vision and assuming at least some risk. An operator, =
on the other hand, has the ability to run an existing thing on a daily =
basis. The skill set required is mostly process optimization, support, =
and steering.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p =
style=3D'mso-margin-top-alt:7.5pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:15.0pt;m=
argin-left:0cm;color:#111!important;line-height:1.6!important;letter-spac=
ing:-0.007em!important'><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'>I think I =
fall more in the starter than operator camp, especially when a product =
requires more on the operation side than starting side. The product we =
sold is a plugin that lives within WordPress. Which is both good and =
bad. Good because lots of folks use WordPress, especially for online =
courses. Bad because WordPress, if not managed well, can become a =
jumbled mess of insanity. And so, while selling our plugin, we quickly =
realized that 90% of support was helping people fix their WordPress =
setup (even though it had nothing to do with our product) and ensuring =
it played nicely with literally thousands of other plugins, all of which =
could be coded with a blatant disregard for =
conventions.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p =
style=3D'mso-margin-top-alt:7.5pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:15.0pt;m=
argin-left:0cm;color:#111!important;line-height:1.6!important;letter-spac=
ing:-0.007em!important'><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'>This isn't =
a slight to WordPress. I think any ecosystem where third-parties create =
things can end up a jumbled mess. But, because of this reality, we were =
averaging one support ticket/thread for every couple sales, which =
amounts to a ton of time spent on support. Too much time for two people. =
For a little comparison, we average less than one support ticket/thread =
per 15-20 customers for my <a href=3D"https://usefathom.com/" =
target=3D"_blank">Fathom Analytics</a> product (stand-alone SaaS app), =
and those tickets don't typically require debugging an entire website or =
group of plugins. Actually, more than half our support tickets are =
either business development questions or feature requests (both are easy =
to deal with).<o:p></o:p></span></p><p =
style=3D'mso-margin-top-alt:7.5pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:15.0pt;m=
argin-left:0cm;color:#111!important;line-height:1.6!important;letter-spac=
ing:-0.007em!important'><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'>A tiny =
company (or &quot;company of one&quot; if you'd like) isn't set up to =
handle that scale of support. Support scaled so close to revenue =
increases. Whereas a larger company, like the one we sold the product =
to, has a dedicated support team and has baked into their company =
infrastructure a way to deal with large volumes of support for large =
volumes of sales. They excel at being an operator company. This is why =
we sold to them - obviously we get a payout, but moreso, we only wanted =
to sell to a company who could on day-one take over support and =
eventually make support even better than we =
could.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p =
style=3D'mso-margin-top-alt:7.5pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:15.0pt;m=
argin-left:0cm;color:#111!important;line-height:1.6!important;letter-spac=
ing:-0.007em!important'><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'>All of =
this is to say, it's been a good lesson for me to think about the =
maintenance cost of success. The product did well in terms of revenue, =
but the cost of that revenue was waking up every day and clearing out a =
support inbox. Yes, we could have hired to solve for this, but =
then&nbsp; I'd have to manage other people (something I'm not interested =
in). It reminds me of <a =
href=3D"https://ofone.co/how-to-build-a-business-you-accidentally-hate/" =
target=3D"_blank">a podcast episode</a> I recorded with my friend Margo =
about &quot;how to build a company you accidentally hate&quot;. The key =
point in the episode being: there=E2=80=99s a difference between the =
business you could run and the business you should =
run.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p =
style=3D'mso-margin-top-alt:7.5pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:15.0pt;m=
argin-left:0cm;color:#111!important;line-height:1.6!important;letter-spac=
ing:-0.007em!important'><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'>In =
learning the lesson above, Jack and I have been very intentional with =
how we build Fathom. We constantly consider how any new feature will =
impact support. We ask ourselves daily, do the decisions we make lead us =
to loving or potentially not loving the operational side of the =
business? We want to continue building a business we should =
run.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p =
style=3D'mso-margin-top-alt:7.5pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:15.0pt;m=
argin-left:0cm;color:#111!important;line-height:1.6!important;letter-spac=
ing:-0.007em!important'><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'>I didn't =
hate the product or customers, but I did grow to feel stressed out about =
the constant deluge of support required to keep it running. And not just =
&quot;oh, I can answer this support question in 10 seconds&quot; but =
&quot;oh, I need full access and an hour or two of mucking about to =
solve this problem&quot;. There are people who excel at those sorts of =
tasks, and I now know I'm not one of them.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p =
style=3D'mso-margin-top-alt:7.5pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:15.0pt;m=
argin-left:0cm;color:#111!important;line-height:1.6!important;letter-spac=
ing:-0.007em!important'><span =
style=3D'font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Helvetica",sans-serif'>So while =
I'll miss working with my cofounder, the awesome customers we had, and =
building out the idea, I won't miss operating the company long term. It =
wasn=E2=80=99t bad work, it was just work I don=E2=80=99t feel suited =
for individually. And I'm so pleased that we found a buyer who's more =
than capable of being an operator and therefore able to keep the product =
going far into the =
future.<o:p></o:p></span></p></td></tr></table></td></tr></table><p =
